Let=E2=80=99s say you want to start an internet business, and you need mone=
y. Here are two ways to raise the money:
=09You incorporate your business and sell stock. This is a pretty tradition=
al way to raise money, and people know how it works. It has some downsides,=
 for you. The main one is that you are giving up some control and ownership=
 of your business: If you sell stock to outsiders, then you will have fiduc=
iary duties to them, you will have to manage the company with their best in=
terests in mind, they might get voting shares and board seats, and they wil=
l own a portion of the value of the business. Another downside is that you =
will be subject to securities regulation. If you sell stock to the public, =
in the US, the US Securities and Exchange Commission will make you register=
 your offering and disclose a lot of stuff about your business. Even if you=
 only sell stock to sophisticated venture capitalists, and thus avoid regis=
tration, you will still be subject to securities=C2=A0fraud=C2=A0rules: If =
you lie to investors to get them to buy your stock, the investors can sue y=
ou, or the SEC can.=09You can sell=C2=A0crypto tokens=C2=A0that are in some=
 way linked to your business. This is a pretty=C2=A0new way to raise money =
for a business, one that=C2=A0had a vogue in the late 2010s and early 2020s=
. But it is much less standardized than stock, and it is not even obvious w=
hat I mean by =E2=80=9Ccrypto tokens that are in some way linked to your bu=
siness.=E2=80=9D Perhaps you start some internet business, you issue some c=
rypto tokens, and you promise to use a portion of the revenue from your bus=
iness to=C2=A0buy back=C2=A0some of those tokens and retire them, to =E2=80=
=9Cbuy and burn=E2=80=9D the tokens. Then if you make a lot of profits, you=
 will buy a lot of tokens, so there will be demand for the tokens and they =
will be valuable. People buy the tokens today to speculate on your future p=
rofitability.
  [1]
 This is a common approach taken by actual crypto companies; we have   talk=
ed a few   times about FTT, the stock-like token that FTX Trading Ltd. issu=
ed in connection with its crypto exchange. But you could imagine other appr=
oaches. You could make the link between your business and the token quite t=
enuous; you could just start a business called Gloobzorp Inc. and issue tok=
ens with the=C2=A0name=C2=A0Gloobzorp and not promise anything, just hoping=
 that people will buy the tokens to bet, incoherently, on the success of yo=
ur business.
  [2]



Which approach should you choose? Well, in, like, 2021, the crypto token ap=
proach had some really powerful things to recommend it:
=09The rules and norms around fiduciary duties, ownership sharing, etc., we=
re much less developed in crypto than they are in stocks. You could issue G=
loobzorp tokens to investors, and raise money, and=C2=A0not=C2=A0give up mu=
ch in the way of control or profits or ownership interests or anything else=
. You could sell shares in the business without selling shares in the busin=
ess =E2=80=94=C2=A0or rather, you could raise money by selling things that =
looked a little bit like shares in the business, without selling shares in =
the business.=09Relatedly, the=C2=A0securities laws=C2=A0=E2=80=A6=C2=A0arg=
uably? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0did not apply to this sort of thing. I mean! There is=
 a lot of argument about that, and we=E2=80=99ll discuss some of it. But yo=
u could at least=C2=A0imagine=C2=A0that these tokens were not securities, w=
hich meant things like (1) you could sell them, broadly, to the public, to =
raise money to build your business, without registering with the SEC or pro=
viding much disclosure,
  [3]
=C2=A0and (2) if you were doing fraud maybe the SEC wouldn=E2=80=99t come a=
fter you.=09There was a huge boom in crypto, money was pouring in, people w=
eren=E2=80=99t asking too many questions, and there was a lot of willingnes=
s to believe that every business with =E2=80=9Ccrypto=E2=80=9D in the descr=
iption would revolutionize economics and make all of its investors rich. So=
 you could raise a lot of money on pretty good terms, without much disclosu=
re, without giving up much control or ownership.

If you had the free choice between (1) raising money subject to a lot of ru=
les about disclosure and honesty and fiduciary duties and (2) raising more=
=C2=A0money with=C2=A0no=C2=A0rules or obligations, wouldn=E2=80=99t you ta=
ke the second option?
But of course, of course, of course, this is not a long-term equilibrium. A=
ll the downsides of stock=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0the fiduciary duties, the sha=
ring of the value of the business, the disclosure obligations =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0are not=C2=A0incidental; they are not just arbitrary punishments visited=
 on entrepreneurs who issue stock.=C2=A0They=E2=80=99re the point. The=C2=
=A0reason=C2=A0that entrepreneurs can raise money by issuing stock =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0they can get real dollars in exchange for pieces of paper saying =
=E2=80=9Cthis is a share of=C2=A0a business that doesn=E2=80=99t exist yet=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that there is a highly developed system of obli=
gations that reassures investors that those pieces of paper have value. The=
 investors get some rights, some control, some economic ownership, some leg=
al and regulatory protections, in exchange for their money. And that is why=
 they are willing to part with their money.=C2=A0
And the particular set of rights that exist in the US =E2=80=94=C2=A0Delawa=
re corporate law, SEC disclosure regulation, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0generally =
works pretty well, to the point that lots of foreign companies come to the =
US to raise money, because subjecting themselves to the burdens of US regul=
ation makes them attractive to investors. Investors trust the US capital ma=
rkets, because they have a long tradition of being pretty well regulated, w=
hich means that they are an attractive place for companies to raise money.
Meanwhile, in=C2=A02024, my description of raising money for a business by =
issuing a crypto token sounds fake and embarrassing. =E2=80=9CWhat on earth=
,=E2=80=9D you probably said as you read it, =E2=80=9Cnobody does this, thi=
s is not a thing.=E2=80=9D I can only say: It really was, in 2021!=C2=A0But=
 now nobody believes that every business with the word =E2=80=9Ccrypto=E2=
=80=9D in its description will revolutionize economics,
  [4]
 people who invested in the earlier crypto offerings   got burned when cryp=
to crashed, and crypto fund-raising is a fraction of what it was a few=C2=
=A0years ago.
If people are willing to give your business money in exchange for=C2=A0noth=
ing=C2=A0then, by all means, take it! But they won=E2=80=99t be willing to =
do that for long.
Meanwhile, these days,=C2=A0the SEC is=C2=A0quite sure=C2=A0that US securit=
ies laws=C2=A0do, and always did, apply to this sort of thing. If you issue=
d a crypto token to fund a business, with vague promises that the token wou=
ld participate in the upside of the business, the SEC thinks that that=E2=
=80=99s just the same as issuing stock, and you should be held to the same =
standards (of disclosure, of not doing fraud) as stock issuers. I   think t=
hey=E2=80=99re   right but that=E2=80=99s not important right now.=C2=A0
The SEC is effecting its crackdown on crypto mostly by going after crypto e=
xchanges. The   thinking is roughly:
=09If all of these crypto tokens are securities, then not only were they al=
l=C2=A0issued illegally (by issuers that didn=E2=80=99t register them with =
the SEC), but they all=C2=A0trade=C2=A0illegally (on crypto exchanges that =
have not registered with the SEC as national securities exchanges).=09There=
 are fewer crypto exchanges than crypto issuers, and they are bigger, and s=
hutting them down will shut down crypto much more efficiently than going af=
ter all the issuers one by one.

One of the SEC=E2=80=99s main targets is Coinbase Global=C2=A0Inc., the big=
 US exchange. The SEC   sued Coinbase in June, and Coinbase is fighting the=
 case hard. Yesterday a New York federal judge held a hearing on Coinbase=
=E2=80=99s motion to dismiss the SEC=E2=80=99s case, and it sounds like it =
went pretty well for Coinbase.  The Wall Street Journal reports:

A federal judge on Wednesday questioned whether allowing the Securities and=
 Exchange Commission to impose its regulations on Coinbase would give the a=
gency sway over markets it doesn=E2=80=99t have authority to supervise.=C2=
=A0
=E2=80=9CI want to understand how your standard does not sweep in the colle=
ctible market or commodities,=E2=80=9D U.S. District Judge Katherine Polk F=
ailla told SEC lawyers in the courtroom. =E2=80=9CIt is a real fear that I =
have that your argument is just sweeping too broadly.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Failla is considering Coinbase=E2=80=99s request to dismiss the SEC=E2=80=
=99s civil lawsuit against it filed in Manhattan federal court. She didn=E2=
=80=99t rule at the end of Wednesday=E2=80=99s five-hour hearing but is exp=
ected to decide in the coming months.=C2=A0

But even if Coinbase wins, there=E2=80=99s something a little hollow about =
the victory.   Bloomberg News reports:

William Savitt, a lawyer for Coinbase, told US District Judge Katherine Pol=
k Failla that tokens trading on the exchange aren=E2=80=99t securities subj=
ect to SEC jurisdiction because buyers don=E2=80=99t gain any rights as a p=
art of their purchases, as they do with stocks or bonds.
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s the difference between buying Beanie Babies Inc. and =
buying Beanie Babies,=E2=80=9D Savitt said. =E2=80=A6
Lawyers for the government responded that buying an item like a baseball ca=
rd or a figurine doesn=E2=80=99t mean that someone is buying a stake in the=
 enterprise that makes such items.
But they said that wasn=E2=80=99t the case with tokens sold on Coinbase.
=E2=80=9CWhen they buy this token, they are investing into the network behi=
nd it,=E2=80=9D SEC lawyer Patrick Costello said. =E2=80=9COne cannot be se=
parated from the other.=E2=80=9D

The SEC=E2=80=99s argument here is that crypto tokens are an investment, pr=
omising some upside from some business building some network with some pote=
ntial to do good things. Coinbase=E2=80=99s argument is that they aren=E2=
=80=99t, that it lists tokens that give investors no rights and that have n=
o claim on any economic activity. Coinbase=E2=80=99s argument is that crypt=
o is a trillion-dollar market for Beanie Babies, that it is not a way to ra=
ise money to fund real business ideas but simply a way to gamble on collect=
ibles. =E2=80=9CNo, see, if you buy a crypto token, you get nothing, so the=
re=E2=80=99s nothing for the SEC to regulate.=E2=80=9D A good legal argumen=
t! But weird=C2=A0marketing!
The problem for crypto is that, to have a big attractive financial market i=
n the long term, you need to have obligations. You need to have some system=
 for ensuring that investors get what they pay for, that entrepreneurs have=
 duties to the investors who give them money, that people deal honestly, th=
at investors get disclosure.
  [5]
 And Coinbase, to be clear, has called for those things: It=C2=A0wants=C2=
=A0regulation=C2=A0of crypto, because in the long run that is good for its =
business; it has  begged the SEC to write new rules for crypto. And I   hav=
e=C2=A0sympathized with its view that some new rules would be nice.
But the SEC  rejected that request, saying, no, actually, the existing=C2=
=A0rules apply to crypto, and are fine. But the crypto market mostly=C2=A0d=
oesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0want existing SEC regulations =E2=80=94=C2=A0the disclo=
sure and anti-fraud rules that apply to stock =E2=80=94 to apply to crypto,=
 because they would be too restrictive. (That=E2=80=99s why Coinbase is fig=
hting the SEC in court, arguing that the SEC has no jurisdiction over crypt=
o at all.) It would be good for crypto to have some rules to eliminate some=
 frauds and make the market more trustworthy, but if you have too many rule=
s and eliminate too many frauds =E2=80=A6 well, you might worry,=C2=A0what =
will be left?
When Coinbase itself went public in 2021, its chief executive officer, Bria=
n Armstrong, wrote  a letter to investors. It was full of big claims:

Coinbase is a company with an ambitious vision: to create more economic fre=
