<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say you want to start an interne=
t business, and you need money. Here are two ways to raise the money:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You incorporate your business and sel=
l stock. This is a pretty traditional way to raise money, and people know h=
ow it works. It has some downsides, for you. The main one is that you are g=
iving up some control and ownership of your business: If you sell stock to =
outsiders, then you will have fiduciary duties to them, you will have to ma=
nage the company with their best interests in mind, they might get voting s=
hares and board seats, and they will own a portion of the value of the busi=
ness. Another downside is that you will be subject to securities regulation=
. If you sell stock to the public, in the US, the US Securities and Exchang=
e Commission will make you register your offering and disclose a lot of stu=
ff about your business. Even if you only sell stock to sophisticated ventur=
e capitalists, and thus avoid registration, you will still be subject to se=
curities=C2=A0<em>fraud=C2=A0</em>rules: If you lie to investors to get the=
m to buy your stock, the investors can sue you, or the SEC can.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can sell=C2=A0<em>crypto tokens=C2=A0</em=
>that are in some way linked to your business. This is a pretty=C2=A0new wa=
y to raise money for a business, one that=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34044144.259401/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTAtMTQvdGhlLXNlYy1yZWFsbHktZG9lc24tdC1sa=
WtlLWljb3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExODI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1f=
c291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMTE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZ=
m/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB712d5a29" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">had a vogue</a> in the late 20=
10s and early 2020s. But it is much less standardized than stock, and it is=
 not even obvious what I mean by =E2=80=9Ccrypto tokens that are in some wa=
y linked to your business.=E2=80=9D Perhaps you start some internet busines=
s, you issue some crypto tokens, and you promise to use a portion of the re=
venue from your business to=C2=A0<em>buy back=C2=A0</em>some of those token=
s and retire them, to =E2=80=9Cbuy and burn=E2=80=9D the tokens. Then if yo=
u make a lot of profits, you will buy a lot of tokens, so there will be dem=
and for the tokens and they will be valuable. People buy the tokens today t=
o speculate on your future profitability.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> This is a common approach taken by actual crypto companies; we have <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34044144.259401/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmFua21=
hbi1mcmllZC1zLWZ0eC1oYWQtYS1kZWF0aC1zcGlyYWwtYmVmb3JlLWJpbmFuY2UtZGVhbD9jbX=
BpZD1CQkQwMTE4MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c=
2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAxMTgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBf35d455f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked</a> a few <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34044144.259401/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTQvZnR4LXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC13YX=
MtYmFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTgyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nvd=
XJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDExOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc018dd26" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  times</a> about FTT, the stock-=
like token that FTX Trading Ltd. issued in connection with its crypto excha=
nge. But you could imagine other approaches. You could make the link betwee=
n your business and the token quite tenuous; you could just start a busines=
s called Gloobzorp Inc. and issue tokens with the=C2=A0<em>name=C2=A0</em>G=
loobzorp and not promise anything, just hoping that people will buy the tok=
ens to bet, incoherently, on the success of your business.<a class=3D"footn=
ote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important=
; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which approach should you choose? Well, in, li=
ke, 2021, the crypto token approach had some really powerful things to reco=
mmend it:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The rules and norms around fiduciary d=
uties, ownership sharing, etc., were much less developed in crypto than the=
y are in stocks. You could issue Gloobzorp tokens to investors, and raise m=
oney, and=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>give up much in the way of control or prof=
its or ownership interests or anything else. You could sell shares in the b=
usiness without selling shares in the business =E2=80=94=C2=A0or rather, yo=
u could raise money by selling things that looked a little bit like shares =
in the business, without selling shares in the business.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Relatedly, the=C2=A0<em>securities laws=C2=A0</em>=
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0arguably? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0did not apply to this sort of thing=
. I mean! There is a lot of argument about that, and we=E2=80=99ll discuss =
some of it. But you could at least=C2=A0<em>imagine=C2=A0</em>that these to=
kens were not securities, which meant things like (1) you could sell them, =
broadly, to the public, to raise money to build your business, without regi=
stering with the SEC or providing much disclosure,<a class=3D"footnote-inde=
x" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displa=
y: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and (2) if you were doing fraud maybe the SEC wouldn=E2=80=99t co=
me after you.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There was a huge boo=
m in crypto, money was pouring in, people weren=E2=80=99t asking too many q=
uestions, and there was a lot of willingness to believe that every business=
 with =E2=80=9Ccrypto=E2=80=9D in the description would revolutionize econo=
mics and make all of its investors rich. So you could raise a lot of money =
on pretty good terms, without much disclosure, without giving up much contr=
ol or ownership.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you had the <em>free choice </em>between (1=
) raising money subject to a lot of rules about disclosure and honesty and =
fiduciary duties and (2) raising <em>more=C2=A0</em>money with=C2=A0<em>no=
=C2=A0</em>rules or obligations, wouldn=E2=80=99t you take the second optio=
n?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But of course, of course, of course, this is n=
ot a long-term equilibrium. All the downsides of stock=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0=
the fiduciary duties, the sharing of the value of the business, the disclos=
ure obligations =E2=80=94=C2=A0are not=C2=A0<em>incidental</em>; they are n=
ot just arbitrary punishments visited on entrepreneurs who issue stock.=C2=
=A0<em>They=E2=80=99re the point</em>. The=C2=A0<em>reason=C2=A0</em>that e=
ntrepreneurs can raise money by issuing stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0they can get r=
eal dollars in exchange for pieces of paper saying =E2=80=9Cthis is a share=
 of=C2=A0a business that doesn=E2=80=99t exist yet=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
is that there is a highly developed system of obligations that reassures in=
vestors that those pieces of paper have value. The investors get some right=
s, some control, some economic ownership, some legal and regulatory protect=
ions, in exchange for their money. And that is why they are willing to part=
 with their money.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the particular set of rights that exist in=
 the US =E2=80=94=C2=A0Delaware corporate law, SEC disclosure regulation, e=
tc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0generally works pretty well, to the point that lots of f=
oreign companies come to the US to raise money, because subjecting themselv=
es to the burdens of US regulation makes them attractive to investors. Inve=
stors trust the US capital markets, because they have a long tradition of b=
eing pretty well regulated, which means that they are an attractive place f=
or companies to raise money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile, in=C2=A0<em>2024</em>, my descripti=
on of raising money for a business by issuing a crypto token sounds fake an=
d embarrassing. =E2=80=9CWhat on earth,=E2=80=9D you probably said as you r=
ead it, =E2=80=9Cnobody does this, this is not a thing.=E2=80=9D I can only=
 say: It really was, in 2021!=C2=A0But now nobody believes that every busin=
ess with the word =E2=80=9Ccrypto=E2=80=9D in its description will revoluti=
onize economics,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> people who invested in the earlier crypto offerings <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34044144.259401/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMDcvd2hlbi1pcy1hLXRva2VuLW5=
vdC1hLXNlY3VyaXR5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTgyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haW=
wmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDExOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZ=
XlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB211cfb85" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  got burned</a> when =
crypto crashed, and crypto fund-raising is a fraction of what it was a few=
=C2=A0years ago.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If people are willing to give your business mo=
ney in exchange for=C2=A0<em>nothing</em>=C2=A0then, by all means, take it!=
 But they won=E2=80=99t be willing to do that for long.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile, these days,=C2=A0the SEC is=C2=A0<e=
m>quite sure=C2=A0</em>that US securities laws=C2=A0<em>do</em>, and always=
 did, apply to this sort of thing. If you issued a crypto token to fund a b=
usiness, with vague promises that the token would participate in the upside=
 of the business, the SEC thinks that that=E2=80=99s just the same as issui=
ng stock, and you should be held to the same standards (of disclosure, of n=
ot doing fraud) as stock issuers. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/34044144.259401/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDctMTQvcmlwcGxlLWlzLWEtc2VjdXJpdHktYW5kLWl0LWlzbi10=
